_metadata.description: Voice recognition difficulty annotations for user data fields

first_names.source: U.S. Social Security Administration - Baby Names
first_names.description: Rankings based on SSA baby name popularity data from 2000-2023
first_names.methodology: Names consistently in top 100 = tier 1, top 500 = tier 2, less common = tier 3, rare in US = tier 4

last_names.source: U.S. Census Bureau - Frequently Occurring Surnames
last_names.description: Rankings based on 2010 Census surname frequency data
last_names.methodology: Names in top 100 surnames = tier 1, top 500 = tier 2, less common = tier 3, rare in US = tier 4

is_phonetically_regular.description: Manual classification based on English phonotactic rules
is_phonetically_regular.methodology: Names flagged as irregular if they contain letter combinations that violate standard English spelling-to-sound correspondences (e.g., 'Ng-' onset, silent letters, vowel combinations with non-English pronunciations)
is_phonetically_regular.limitations: Classification is based on standard American English; regional accents may affect perception

has_common_homophones.description: Names with genuinely common alternative spellings

syllable_count.description: Algorithmic syllable counting using vowel-group heuristic
syllable_count.methodology: Count consecutive vowel groups (aeiouy), adjust for silent 'e' endings
syllable_count.limitations: Heuristic-based; may be off by 1 for some names with unusual patterns

email.description: Email analysis for voice recognition difficulty
components_analyzed: has_numbers - whether email contains digits that must be spelled
digit_count - number of digits requiring spelling
domain_is_common - whether domain is well-known (gmail, yahoo, etc.)
local_part_inherits_name_difficulty - name features that affect local part
email.methodology: Emails parsed into local_part and domain; numbers extracted; difficulty inherited from name analysis

domain_analysis.description: Domain difficulty based on phonetic regularity, not just popularity
factors: name_has_numbers - does domain name contain digits?
name_is_known_word - is it a recognized English word or brand?
name_is_simple_word - is it all letters, 3+ chars?
domain_analysis.note: 'example.com' does NOT need spelling - 'example' is a standard English word

transcription_difficulty.description: Likelihood of correct transcription from natural speech (without spelling)

levels.hard: Low likelihood of correct transcription without spelling

names.description: First and last names scored by risk factors

phonetically_irregular.description: Spelling does not match English phonetic expectations

has_common_homophones.description: Multiple valid spellings sound the same

frequency_tier_4.description: Name is uncommon in US population data

frequency_tier_3.description: Name is less common in US population data

email.description: Email difficulty inherits from name components
email.logic: Takes the maximum difficulty of first_name and last_name
notes: Domain 'example.com' is a standard English word (easy)
Name parts in local_part inherit their transcription difficulty

logic.easy: Standard zip code, no problematic patterns
logic.medium: Contains triple-repeated digits (e.g., '888') which may cause count confusion

zip.notes: Individual digits are unambiguous when spoken clearly

address1.description: Street address format: '### Street Name Type'

logic.easy: All street name words are common English words
logic.medium: Contains unusual or uncommon street name words

address1.notes: Street numbers spoken digit-by-digit are unambiguous

address2.logic: Always easy - 'Suite' is standard, numbers are digit-by-digit

state.logic: Always easy - standard abbreviations are well-known

tier_definitions.1: very_common_top_100 - Name appears in top 100 of SSA/Census rankings
tier_definitions.2: common_top_500 - Name appears in top 500 of SSA/Census rankings
tier_definitions.3: less_common - Name is recognized but not in top 500
tier_definitions.4: uncommon_in_us - Name is rare in US population data
